04344nam a22006615i 9780814728925DE-B159720200623100627.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200623t19961996nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147289257 a10.18574/97808147289252doi  a(DE-B1597)548044  a(OCoLC)45843998  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHQ75.6.U5 7aSOC0280002bisacsh04a306.76631 aFranzen, Trisha, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSpinsters and Lesbians :bIndependent Womanhood in the United States /cTrisha Franzen. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[1996] 4cÂ©1996  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Cutting Edge ;v600tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgments -- tProgressive Era Spinsters -- tContemporary Lesbians -- tIntroduction. Spinsters and Lesbians -- tONE. "What Are You Going to Be?" -- tTWO. "I Knew I Was Odd" -- tTHREE. "O, the Glorious Privilege of Being Independent" -- tFOUR. "I Was Going to Have to Do It All on My Own" -- tFIVE. "Such Beautiful Lives Together" -- tSIX. "We're Not the Only Ones" -- tSEVEN. Spinsters and Lesbians -- tOn Methodology -- tAppendix. Tables -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAmericans have long held fast to a rigid definition of womanhood, revolving around husband, home, and children. Women who rebelled against this definition and carved out independent lives for themselves have often been rendered invisible in U.S. history.In this unusual comparative study, Trisha Franzen brings to light the remarkable lives of two generations of autonomous women: Progressive Era spinsters and mid-twentieth century lesbians. While both groups of women followed similar paths to independence--separating from their families, pursuing education, finding work, and creating woman-centered communities--they faced different material and cultural challenge and came to claim very different identities. Many of the turn-of-the-century women were prominent during their time, from internationally recognized classicist Edith Hamilton through two early Directors of the Women's Bureau, Mary Anderson and Freida Miller. Maturing during the time of a broad and powerful women's movement, they were among that era's new women, the often-single women who were viewed as in the vanguard of women's struggle for equality. In contrast, never-married women after World War II, especially lesbians, were considered beyond the pale of real womanhood. Before the women's and gay/lesbian liberation movements, they had no positive contemporary images of alternative lives for women. Highlighting the similarities and differences between women-oriented women confronting changing gender and sexuality systems, Spinsters and Lesbians thus traces a continuum among women who constructed lives outside institutionalized heterosexuality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aFeminismzUnited States. 0aLesbianismzUnited States. 0aSingle womenzUnited States. 0aWomenzUnited StatesvBiography. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814728925423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814728925.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK